title: Single-Ascending Dose, Safety, Tolerability, Pharmacokinetic, and Pharmacodynamic Study of LY2886721 in Healthy Subjects
description_brief: This is a Phase 1 study in healthy subjects to evaluate the safety and tolerability of LY2886721 single doses, how the body handles the drug, and the drug's effect on the body.
description_detailed: This is a Phase 1 study with 2 parts, both in healthy subjects. Part 1 is a subject- and investigator-blind, placebo-controlled, randomized, 3-period, crossover study. Part 1 will assess the safety and tolerability of LY2886721 single doses, how the body handles the drug, and the drug's effect on the body. Part 2 is a subject- and investigator-blind, placebo-controlled, randomized study to assess the safety and tolerability of an LY2886721 single dose, how the body handles the drug, and the drug's effect on the body including in cerebrospinal fluid.

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails: The study consists of 2-parts. Part A was a cross-over study and was conducted in 2 alternating cohorts (Cohorts A and B). Part B was a single-dose, single period study in 2 cohorts (Cohorts C and D). All doses were administered in the fasted state, unless otherwise indicated. Each oral dose was followed by a washout period of at least 14 days.

outcomeMeasures.title: Number of Participants With Clinically Significant Effects (Adverse Events)
outcomeMeasures.description: A summary of serious adverse events and other nonserious adverse events located in Reported Adverse Event section. To assess effect of food on pharmacokinetics of LY2886721, participants in Cohort B during Period 3 (1 period=8 days) of Part 1 fasted overnight for at least 8 hours prior to receiving a single 7-milligram (mg) oral dose of LY2886721 in the fed state (Part 1 - Fed). Participants in other LY2886721 groups received LY2886721 in fasted state. Due to crossover design in Part 1, results reported by treatment; thus, participants are included in multiple arms.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: 39 of the 40 participants who were entered and randomized into the study and who had undergone study procedures were included in the safety analyses. One participant, who was entered and randomized into the study but did not undergo study procedures, was excluded from the analysis.
outcomeMeasures.timeFrame: Predose to 10-14 days after final dose of study drug (up to 42 days)

drug: LY2886721 (Eli Lilly) — BACE1 (beta‑secretase) inhibitor; small‑molecule amyloid‑lowering agent
explanation_target: Reason: The study title/description is a Phase 1 single‑ascending dose safety/tolerability/pharmacokinetic/pharmacodynamic trial of LY2886721 in healthy subjects (NCT record / trial listing). citeturn0search5turn0search8

Act: LY2886721 is a potent, selective BACE1 (beta‑site APP cleaving enzyme 1) inhibitor that dose‑dependently lowers Aβ in plasma and CSF in animals and humans, consistent with an anti‑amyloid, disease‑modifying mechanism. This identifies it as a small‑molecule drug targeting Alzheimer's pathology. citeturn0search3turn0search1
Act (additional sources): Therapeutics summaries and drug databases also describe LY2886721 as a BACE inhibitor developed by Eli Lilly for AD. citeturn0search0turn0search2

Act (safety note): Lilly voluntarily terminated a Phase II study of LY2886721 in June 2013 due to abnormal liver biochemical tests identified during monitoring — relevant to its development but not to category assignment. citeturn0search7turn0search10

Reflect / Classification: The intervention is a small‑molecule inhibitor of a core AD pathway (BACE1 → amyloid β production). That fits the definition of 'disease‑targeted small molecule' rather than a biologic, cognitive enhancer, or neuropsychiatric symptomatic treatment. No substantive ambiguity in the description. citeturn0search3turn0search0
explanation_agent: Reason: LY2886721 is a small‑molecule inhibitor of BACE1 (beta‑site APP cleaving enzyme 1), the protease that initiates production of amyloid‑β (Aβ); therefore the drug’s mechanism is directly aimed at lowering amyloid beta. citeturn0search5turn0search3

Act: Trial details — LY2886721 (Eli Lilly) is described in multiple sources as a potent, selective BACE1 inhibitor that dose‑dependently lowers Aβ in plasma and CSF in animals and humans, consistent with an anti‑amyloid, disease‑modifying mechanism. It was advanced into Phase 2 but development was halted after abnormal liver biochemistry was detected in routine monitoring. citeturn0search1turn0search4turn0search0

Reflect: Classification — The intervention targets the amyloid production pathway (BACE1 → Aβ) and is a disease‑targeted small molecule, so the most specific CADRO category is A) Amyloid beta. There is no indication in the description of multi‑target activity, symptomatic (neurotransmitter) action, or a non‑therapeutic diagnostic focus, so 'A) Amyloid beta' is appropriate. citeturn0search5turn0search6

Web search results / supporting sources (selected): 1) PubMed article reporting preclinical and early clinical Aβ lowering by LY2886721. citeturn0search5 2) Eli Lilly press release (June 13, 2013) announcing voluntary termination of the Phase II study due to abnormal liver biochemical tests. citeturn0search0 3) Drug/compound summary (NCATS/drug database) and ALZFORUM therapeutic entry describing Phase 1/2 development and CSF/plasma Aβ effects. citeturn0search1turn0search4 4) RCSB PDB entry showing crystal structure of BACE with LY2886721 (structural evidence of BACE1 binding). citeturn0search3 5) Review/discovery article noting LY2886721 development halted for elevated liver enzymes and contextualizing other BACE programs. citeturn0search6
